g.text: YT Dislike Fetcher
YT Dislike Proxy
YouTube API
First, YT Dislike Fetcher interacts directly with YouTube's servers, logging in and receiving
an OAuth Bearer API token with the "youtube.readonly" scope. The fetcher can also ask
the YouTube API for video IDs whose dislikes should be requested.
YT Dislike Fetcher opens an HTTP proxy
over TLS.
Connection Established. This response
includes a header with a UUID for this proxy
session.
YT Dislike Fetcher requests dislikes from
YouTube, initiating a TLS connection directly
with the YouTube API through the proxy.
Request is forwarded to YouTube API. Messages
are opaque to the proxy, which keeps the creator's
OAuth token private.
YT Dislike Proxy is recording the encrypted TLS
traffic sent from the YouTube API to YT Dislike
Fetcher, but cannot (at this stage) decrypt the
response, because TLS creates a secure tunnel
between the fetcher and the YouTube API.
YouTube API returns dislike counts, still opaque
to the proxy.
Response from YouTube is forwarded to the
YT Dislike Fetcher, which can (but does not
need to) decrypt and read it.
Instead of deleting all ephemeral TLS keys
used in the exchange, YT Dislike Fetcher
retains the
server traffic key
from the
YouTube request, which was used to encrypt
YouTube's response to the API request (but
not the request, which was encrypted with
the client traffic key).
YT Dislike Fetcher sends the server traffic key
(via HTTPS) to YT Dislike Proxy alongside the
UUID associated with the proxy session.
Now, YT Dislike Proxy can decrypt the previously-captured response
from the YouTube API. Since YT Dislike Fetcher did not send the
client
traffic key, YT Dislike Proxy
cannot
read the API
request
, which
contains API credentials sent by YT Dislike Fetcher, even if the
proxy did capture that traffic.
If the response from YouTube matches the expected format, YT Dislike
Proxy ingests the fetched dislike counts and returns to the fetcher.
Response (2xx or 4xx, depending on ingestion
success)
